<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier Speaks Highly of Japan's High-Tech Advancement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OSAKA, November 15 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Chinese Premier Li Peng
said here today that he was deeply impressed by the progress Japan
has made in the high-tech area.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with four major Japanese newspapers, Li, who is
on a six-day official good-will visit to Japan, said China has
achieved great progress since he visited Japan eight years
ago. Japan, he said, has also made remarkable progress in the same
period, particularly in the high-tech area.
</P>
<P>
After visiting Tokyo where he held talks with Prime Minister
Ryutaro Hashimoto, Li continued his tour of Japan to Nagoya, Osaka
and other cities where he visited several leading Japanese auto
and electronics firms.
</P>
<P>
Li said the warm reception he has received throughout the trip
demonstrates the friendly sentiments of the Japanese people to the
Chinese.
</P>
<P>
At the request of reporters, Li reiterated the explanation made
by Japan on the Japan-U.S. security cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"Prime Minister Hashimoto has told me that the new
Japan-U.S. security cooperation guideline is of a defensive
nature, in conformity with the framework of Japan's constitution,
and does not run counter to the basic principles enshrined in the
Sino-Japanese Joint Statement and the Sino-Japanese Treaty of
Peace and Friendship," Li noted.
</P>
<P>
"I understand the explanation made by Prime Minister
Hashimoto," Li said. It would be perfect if Hashimoto would
clarify that such cooperation does not involve or include Taiwan,
he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
