<HEADLINE> Li Peng on China's Financial Situation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OSAKA, November 15 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Chinese Premier Li Peng
said here today that China, for the time being, has no plan to
readjust the exchange rate between the renminbi and the
U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
Li, who is on a six-day official good-will visit to Japan, made
the remark when asked to comment on the financial crisis in some
regions in the world and its influence on China, particularly Hong
Kong, during an interview with four major Japanese newspapers.
</P>
<P>
Li said China's current financial situation remains stable. The
exchange rate is one U.S. dollar to 8.3 yuan. Therefore, "we have
no plan to make a readjustment," he added.
</P>
<P>
The (financial) situation in Hong Kong, he said, is all right
and the exchange rate between the HK dollar and the U.S. dollar
remains stable, although Hong Kong was struck by the crisis that
began in Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
China pursues the "one country, two systems" policy and the
government of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region is in
charge of economic operations in Hong Kong, Li said.
</P>
<P>
He said the central government supports the linked currency
system of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Li said the close link between Hong Kong and the inland areas
and the sustained economic development of the interior areas is
the best support for Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of China's attitude on the establishment of the Asian
monetary fund, Li said China is not opposed to discussions on this
matter by experts first. He said Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto holds a similar view. 
</P>
</TEXT>
