<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Sacks Privatization Officials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, November 15 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
today fired two senior privatization officials Maxim Boiko and
Pyotr Mostovoi for their involvement in the scandal over high fees
received for writing an as-of-yet unpublished book.
</P>
<P>
Also embroiled in the scandal was the first Deputy Prime
Minister Anatoly Chubais and two other officials, who reportedly
received 90,000 dollars each for writing a book entitled "A
History of Russian Privatization."
</P>
<P>
The authors constitute the bulk of Russia's privatization team.
</P>
<P>
The book involved the authors in the scandal because of
allegations that the payment is a bribe in disguise.
</P>
<P>
Yelstin strongly criticized Chubais' activities as "not
acceptable" but declined his resignation, the Interfax and
ITAR-TASS reported.
</P>
<P>
Chubais conceded Friday the fees were too high and submitted a
resignation to Yeltsin earlier today.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, Yeltsin dismissed his first deputy chief of staff
Alexander Kazakov for involvement in the scandal.
</P>
<P>
The fifth co-author, former privatization chief Alfred Kokh, is
reportedly under investigation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
