<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwaiti Foreign Minister Visits Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, November 15 (Xinhua) -- Kuwaiti First Deputy Prime
Minister and Foreign Minister Sheikh Sabah Al-Ahmad Al-Jaber
Al-Sabah arrived here this afternoon for a two-day visit to Egypt.
</P>
<P>
The visit is believed to focus on the latest development in the
Gulf region and aim at enlisting Cairo's support in an
international unity against Iraqi President Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
Upon arrival at the airport, Sabah said that his visit comes
within the framework of continual consultation between the two
countries and between Kuwaiti Emir Sheikh Jaber Al-Ahmad Al-Sabah
and Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that he will deliver a message to Mubarak from the
Kuwaiti emir, but refused to give any details of the message.
</P>
<P>
"Egypt and Syria are our allies... and are indispensable to
us," said the Kuwaiti diplomat, who will also travel to Syria and
Lebanon in a regional tour.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Deputy Premier Tariq Aziz is also expected in town today
for talks with the Egyptian leadership in an effort to find a way
out of the current crisis between Baghdad and the U.S. and
U.N. Special Commission monitoring Iraq's weapons destruction.
</P>
<P>
Aziz, due here from Paris, will also visit Tunisia, Libya,
Algeria and Morocco to seek Arab support.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait has hoped for tougher sanctions and military strikes
against Iraq, the hostile neighbor whose troops trampled the
small, oil-rich sheikhdom seven years ago.
</P>
<P>
Kuwaiti Undersecretary for Foreign Affairs Soliman Majed
al-Shaheen told the Middle East News Agency earlier that Sabah's
visit was aimed to discuss the latest developments in the Gulf
region.
</P>
<P>
Sabah will hold talks with the Egyptian side on issues of
mutual concern on the eve of the Gulf Cooperation Council summit
in Kuwait and the Organization of the Islamic Conference summit in
Iranian capital Tehran, Shaheen said.
</P>
<P>
Both the summits are due in December. 
</P>
</TEXT>
