<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier Visits Osaka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OSAKA, Japan 15 (Xinhua) -- Governor of Osaka Prefecture of
Japan Nokku Yokoyama pledged today that the prefecture will make
greater contributions to the development of Japan-China friendship
and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
At a banquet held in honor of visiting Chinese Premier Li Peng
here tonight, Yokoyama said economic and cultural exchanges
between Osaka Prefecture and China had started before the
normalization of Japan-China diplomatic ties and thus the
prefecture has been playing the role of a bridge for exchanges
between Japan and China.
</P>
<P>
The prefecture and quite a few cities in the prefecture have
now established ties of friendship and cooperation with various
cities in China and exchanges between them are getting more and
more close with many enterprises in the prefecture now have
cooperation projects in China, said the governor.
</P>
<P>
In his speech at the banquet, Li Peng said great changes had
taken place in the City of Osaka since his last visit to the city
in 1984. The international airport in Osaka, built on a ground
made by filling up part of the sea, shortened the distance of air
travel between Osaka and Shanghai of China, thus facilitating
exchanges between them, said the Chinese premier.
</P>
<P>
Li expressed the hope that the prefecture will continue to play
the role of a bridge in the development of friendship and
cooperation between China and Japan by enlarging cooperation with
China in various fields, particularly in high technology.
</P>
<P>
He said that Matsushita Electric Industrial Co., Ltd in Osaka
showed him quite a few high-tech products during his visit to the
company here this afternoon and that he welcomes other enterprises
in the area to enter into cooperation with China.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that people-to-people exchanges will also
increase apart from exchanges between the governments of the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Li came to Osaka this morning from Nagoya in Aichi Prefecture
where he paid a visit to Toyota Motor Corp.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese premier arrived in Tokyo on November 11 for a
six-day official good-will visit to Japan. He is expected to visit
Nara before ending his current trip to the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
