<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier on International Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OSAKA, November 15 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Chinese Premire Li Peng
said here today that the recent exchange of visits between leaders
of China, the United States, Russia and Japan is in a sense an
indicator of the acceleration of the world's multipolarization
process.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with four leading Japanese newspapers, Li, who
is on a six-day official good-will visit to Japan, said China
pursues an independent and all-round foreign policy of peace, and
keeps broad contacts with many countries in the world.
</P>
<P>
Responding to a question on the possibility of establishing
dialogues between the above-mentioned four nations, Li said many
multilateral dialogue mechanisms have already been established,
some of which play a positive role in international relations.
</P>
<P>
But it is more important to strengthen bilateral ties among
countries, Li said. The development of state-to-state relations
should be based on the basic principles of mutual respect,
equality and mutual benefit, and non-interference in each other's
internal affairs, he added.
</P>
<P>
On the forthcoming international environmental conference
scheduled for December in Kyoto, Li said that China is carrying
out a strategy of sustained development and environmental
protection, which is a basic policy of China.
</P>
<P>
"We have always attached importance to climate changes and
China has always participated actively in the global environment
campaign," the premier said.
</P>
<P>
Li went on to say that the environment is a global issue and
that all countries should work for environmental protection
according to their own conditions. It is unfair and impossible to
apply a unified standard on all countries, he said.
</P>
<P>
It is unreasonable for developed countries to apply their own
standards or even set up restrictions on developing countries, he
added.
</P>
<P>
"We hope the Kyoto conference will make positive progress
through equal consultations," the premier said.
</P>
<P>
In reply to a question concerning the situation in Iraq, Li
said China hopes Iraq will resume cooperation with the United
Nations as soon as possible and fully implement relevant U.N.
resolutions to ensure the U.N. inspection.
</P>
<P>
"We hope the dispute will be settled through peaceful
negotiations rather than resorting to force," Li noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
