<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Renews Threat to Gun Down U-2 Plane </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, November 15 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Foreign Minister
Mohammed Saeed al-Sahhaf today renewed the threat to shoot down
any U.S. U-2 spy plane overflying Iraq on U.N. arms inspection
missions.
</P>
<P>
"Surely we'll shoot it down" if the surveillance plane resumes
overflight again, al-Sahhaf said while fielding questions from
reporters at a news briefing here this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
In his statement, the foreign minister lashed out at the
U.S. hostile policy against Iraq and its objective to keep the
sanctions in place and use them as a tool to topple President
Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
Drawing a line between U.N. and U.S. aims, he claimed the
sanctions, "under the evil guide and leader" of the U.S., are
designed to achieve American objectives rather than compliance of
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
He further accused Washington of trying to materialize its
conspiracy to replace the "patriotic political system in Iraq"
with a puppet regime.
</P>
<P>
He said Iraq wants a political and diplomatic solution to the
current crisis because it is "the right way" and Iraq will "do its
utmost to see this prevails."
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Deputy Premier Tariq Aziz is due in Cairo, Egypt today as
part of a tour of five northern African Arab countries, which also
include Libya, Algeria, Tunisia and Morocco, in an effort to seek
more Arab support in Iraq's standoff with the U.S. and the
U.N. Special Commission monitoring weapons destruction in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Al-Sahhaf asked the U.N. to adopt a "fair approach" to the
crisis and give Baghdad a chance for in-depth discussion and
dialogue with the Security Council in the presence of those
related to the crisis.
</P>
<P>
He said the council should listen to Iraq's "just requests and
demands" as part of a mechanism on how to finalize the
U.N. weapons inspection work "fully, fairly and practically" in
order to lift U.N. sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Denying that Iraq is preparing for a military confrontation, he
said Baghdad is not on a war footing. He explained that Iraq's gas
rationing taking effect today is a precaution and safety measure
to empty oil tanks and depots to avoid large explosions and
casualties in case of a military strike by the U.S. and its allies.
</P>
<P>
U.S. aircraft carrier George Washington, together with its
combat group, is on the way to the Persian Gulf and will need one
week before joining another carrier USS Nimitz which is already
patrolling there.
</P>
<P>
America's closest ally, Britain, has announced it is sending
aircraft carrier Invincible to the region to reinforce U.S.
military buildup.
</P>
<P>
"It is muscle-flexing within the preparation to lauch an attack
on Iraq," al-Sahhaf pointed out, vowing that Iraq will defend its
security and sovereignty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
