<HEADLINE> Egypt Warns of Setback in Mideast Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, November 15 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
said today that the Middle East peace process is now in a blind
alley, and warned of a comeback of violence and destruction in the
region.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a joint session of the People's Assembly and the
Shura (Advisory) Council, Mubarak demanded that Israel fully
implement the agreements signed with the Palestinians, especially
the Oslo accords, as an essential step to maintain peace impetus
and prevent a return of war-like atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
"Negotiations and meetings are not an objective in itself, but
a way to reach the essential aim which is to achieve a tangible
progress on the road to peace," said Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
He said that a just and lasting peace is the only means to
maintain regional security and stability.
</P>
<P>
He called upon Israel to abide by its commitments enshrined in
signed agreements and relevant principles to keep the momentum of
the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
He also urged Israel to pave the way for resuming negotiations
on the Lebanese and Syrian tracks and stop obstructing the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak lauded the efforts by all parties concerned, mainly the
United States, the European Union and Russia, to push forward the
Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he called on Arab countries to boost economic
cooperation and implement the resolutions adopted by the Arab
Economic Unity Council in 1964 that call for setting up an Arab
Common Market.
</P>
<P>
He urged Arab countries to join hands in implementing a number
of national projects that will serve Arab economy in general and
boost its collective power to meet challenges. 
</P>
</TEXT>
