<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Export Level Puzzles City Economists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, November 15 (Xinhua) -- Economists in the City of
London are puzzled by the resilience of UK's export volumes in the
face of sterling's strength.
</P>
<P>
Despite sterling's appreciation of some 20 percent since August
1996, there has been little reduction in the volume of exports,
according to the latest Inflation Report by the Bank of England.
</P>
<P>
The Bank cited a number of possible explanations including the
use of fixed short-term contracts, slow adjustment of relative
prices and perceptions that the rise in sterling may not last.
</P>
<P>
Foreign exporters may also be raising profit margins rather
than exploiting the boost to their competitiveness by pursuing a
bigger share of the UK market.
</P>
<P>
"As the relatively high value of sterling has persisted since
the August report, some of these factors may start to unwind," the
Bank said.
</P>
<P>
It added that exporters may have been concentrating their
efforts on markets such as the United States, where domestic
demand was stronger and where sterling's appreciation had been
less dramatic.
</P>
<P>
The Bank did not believe exporters could hold out forever.
"With recovery in continental Europe, demand prospects in UK
export markets seem relatively bright, despite the likely fall in
Asian activity," the report said.
</P>
<P>
But UK net exports are still expected to fall further during
the coming quarters, as the effects of sterling's appreciation
continue to feed through, according to the Bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
