<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-15 19:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Intensifies Campaign against Narcotics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, November 15 (Xinhua) -- Iran today amended its
anti-drug law to intensify crackdown on narcotics-related crimes,
the Iranian official news agency IRNA reported.
</P>
<P>
The revised law stipulates tougher punishments for narcotics
crimes and allows the use of labor camps to rehabilitate the
offenders.
</P>
<P>
IRNA quoted an authoritative source named as saying that major
offenders - drug dealers and traffickers would be sent to hard
labor camps.
</P>
<P>
Drug addiction is a crime in Iran, but addicts would not be
prosecuted during their rehabilitation period.
</P>
<P>
The new law empowered the Iranian president, who also headed
the anti-narcotics campaign headquarters, to utilize all
facilities at the executive branch's disposal to fight the social
menace.
</P>
<P>
Iran passed the anti-drug law in 1989, under which any drug
trafficker caught with more than 30 grams of heroin or 5,000 grams
of opium would be sentenced to death.
</P>
<P>
Official reports said that more than 4,000 drug traffickers had
been executed since the law took effect.
</P>
<P>
During last Iranian calendar year ending March 20, Iran seized
a total of 175 tons of narcotics and arrested 12,000 drug
smugglers.
</P>
<P>
However, drug trafficking is still one of the main, serious
social problems in Iran, which is one of the major transit routes
for drugs destined for Europe from the "Golden Crescent" in the
border areas linking Pakistan and Afghanistan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
