<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Rejects Chubais's Resignation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, November 15 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
today turned down the resignation from First Deputy Prime Minister
and finance Minister Anatoly Chubais, the Kremlin press service
said.
</P>
<P>
The president in a telephone call criticized Chubais for being
among the authors of a book on privatization and warned him
against such steps in the future, but rejected the minister's
resignation request.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin did not accept Chubais's resignation because of "an
extremely critical economic situation in Russia".
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Yeltsin sacked two senior officials -- Maxim
Boiko as deputy prime minister and state property minister and
Pyotr Mostovoi as deputy chief of the presidential administration.
</P>
<P>
All these officials, including two others, were among the book
deal. Each of the authors, including Chubais, received 90,000 U.S.
Dollars fee for the unpublished book on privatization in Russia,
thereby stirring up a major political scandal.
</P>
<P>
The press service said Yeltsin had asked the Prosecutor
General's Office for documents on the case and had decided that
the involved in the scandal officials' receipt of such large fees
did not constitute legal offenses but was improper.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin dismissed his staff's first deputy chief Alexander
Kazakov on Friday, who was reportedly also involved in the book
scandal. 
</P>
