<HEADLINE> German Greens Pledge to Fight for Renewal in Germany </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, November 15 (Xinhua) -- One of the Germany's opposition
parties, the Greens, today pledged to fight for a social and
ecological renewal of the country in the next general elections in
September 1998.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the party congress in the central German city of
Kassel, the Greens' parliamentary group leader, Joschka Fischer
held German Chancellor Helmut Kohl responsible for the political
standstill in Bonn and for the country's record-high unemployment
of about 4.3 million.
</P>
<P>
A fundamental political change in Bonn was only possible with
the participation of the Greens, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Greens has been seeking to join hand with Bonn's main
opposition party, the Social Democratic Party (SPD), to replace
Kohl's centre-right ruling coalition which has been in power since
1982.
</P>
<P>
The two opposition parties in Bonn have managed to form ruling
coalitions in five of Germany's 16 federal states so far.
</P>
<P>
However, in order to achieve the power change in Bonn, Fischer
urged his party to exclude its radical demands, such as the
abolition of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO), from
its election platform.
</P>
<P>
Most recent German opinion polls show that if the elections
were held today, Kohl's ruling parties would lose to a coalition
of the SPD and the Greens. 
</P>
