<HEADLINE> Military Actions in Tanzania Refugee Camps Denied </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, November 15 (Xinhua) -- A joint security
mission formed recently by the United Nations and Tanzania to
investigate activities of refugees in their camps in Tanzania has
ended military activities in the camps.
</P>
<P>
The joint security commission was formed by the United Nations
High Commission for Refugees (UNHCR) and the Tanzanian government
to investigate allegations by the Tutsi authority that the camps
were being used to train rebels.
</P>
<P>
"There is no militarization in Tanzania refugee camps," said
Vincent Parker, Senior External Relations Officer with UNHCR.
</P>
<P>
He was speaking to journalists Friday in Dar es Salaam at a
press conference where he revealed the findings of the
commission.
</P>
<P>
He said that the mission, which carried out its fact-finding
investigations in the camps last May, did not get proof that the
camps were being used to train Burundi rebels, as claimed by the
Pierre Buyoya's authority, The Guardian reported today.
</P>
<P>
Buyoya's fears are baseless, Parker said.
</P>
<P>
He said the mission noticed increased political activities in
the camps as people were vocal in identifying themselves with
their political parties.
</P>
<P>
Burundi troops have attacked Tanzania twice this year,
claiming that the country was training Burundi rebels in refugee
camps. Tanzania categorically denied these claims and repulsed
both attacks.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the suspension of the exercise to repatriate
Congolese refugees, Parker said consultations were currently
going on between the UNHCR and the governments of Tanzania and
the Democratic Republic of the Congo to facilitate its
resumption.
</P>
<P>
He said developments in the eastern part of the Congo, leading
particularly to lack of security, caused the suspension of the
repatriation exercise.
</P>
<P>
UNHCR is more interested in the welfare of the refugees than
only ferrying them home, said Parker, stressing that the
environment at home should be conducive for their return.
</P>
<P>
He said most of the refugees are willing to go home and engage
themselves in development activities.
</P>
<P>
So far more than 51,400 Congolese refugees, camped in Kigoma
region, have registered themselves for voluntary repatriation, he
said.
</P>
<P>
A total of 7,003 Congolese refugees had been repatriated by
October 27. Some other 13,000 refugees had gone home through
spontaneous repatriation.
</P>
<P>
On the government's special operation launched on September 20
to round up aliens and refugees staying out of their camps, he
said more than 14,304 refugees netted in operation had been sent
to their respective camps. But the operation also led to the
separation of families.  
</P>
</TEXT>
