<HEADLINE> Kuwaiti Delegation Leaves for Doha Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, November 15 (Xinhua) -- The Kuwaiti delegation
left here today for Qatari capital Doha to attend the Middle East
and North Africa (MENA) economic conference, the Kuwaiti News
Agency (KNA) reported.
</P>
<P>
The delegation, headed by undersecretary of the Finance
Ministry, Abdel Mohsen Al-Hanif, will discuss with other
participants ways to promote commercial activities in the region,
KNA said.
</P>
<P>
The theme of the three-day Doha conference due to open on
Sunday is "creation of new participation for the private and
public sectors for growth of trade and economy after the year
2000."
</P>
<P>
The MENA conference, originally aimed at integrating the
Mideast economy along with progress of the peace process, has
split the Arab world because of the peace crisis since March.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait, Jordan, Oman, Tunisia, Yemen, Comoros and Mauritania
have decided to participate the conference, while Egypt, Saudi
Arabia, Morocco, the United Arab Emirates, Algeria, Syria, Lebanon
and Bahrain preferred to stay away.
</P>
<P>
Those on the boycott front contend that Israel should not be
rewarded with the economic opportunity while the peace process is
deadlocked due to its hardline policy.
</P>
<P>
But Kuwait has argued that attending the conference along with
Israel does not mean it will establish any kind of relations with
the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
The Kuwaiti Chamber of Commerce and Industry has said it would
not participate in the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait at present does not have economic relations with Israel
and has halted the normalization process after Israel broke ground
to build a Jewish settlement in East Jerusalem last March. 
</P>
</TEXT>
