<HEADLINE> Turkey Vows to Defend Turkish Cypriots </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, November 15 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Chief of General Staff
Ismail Hakki Karadayi said today in northern Cyprus that Turkey
will do whatever it can to defend the interests of the Turkish
Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a banquet in Girne, a port city, marking the 14th
anniversary of the founding of "the Turkish Republic of Northern
Cyprus," Karadayi said that Turkey will maintain its military
existence on the eastern Mediterranean island.
</P>
<P>
Turkey landed its troops on the east Mediterranean island in
1974 and took over the northern third in the wake of a short-lived
pro-Athens coup. The Turkish Cypriots declared in 1983 the
breakaway Turkish Republic recognized only by Ankara.
</P>
<P>
"We, soliders, are here with our tanks and guns, and there will
be peace," Karadayi said.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been split into a Greek Cypriot-controlled south and
a Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 and Turkey has since
maintained 35,000 troops in the northern third.
</P>
<P>
Karadayi expressed Turkey's determination to thwart any threats
to Turkish Cypriots, saying that Turkey's fate is closely related
with that of northern Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
The international community has been making efforts for years
to help reunify the island on bi-zonal and bi-communal basis, but
no tangible progress has been achieved.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, some Greek Cypriot protesters tried to enter
the Turkish Cypriot-controlled area, but were barred by police and
the United Nations peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
Four Greek Cypriots and one Turkish Cypriot were killed last
year in bloody clashes along the buffer zone. 
</P>
</TEXT>
