<HEADLINE> Writethru: MENA Conference Opens Despite Boycott </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DOHA, November 16 (Xinhua) -- The controversial Middle East
and North Africa (MENA) Economic Conference opened here today
despite an extensive boycott by Arab countries against Israelis'
participation.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. tried hard to downplay the influence of the
boycott by strongly advocating the philosophy that Arab-Israeli
economic cooperation will boost the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Some 2,000 delegates, mostly businessmen from 66 countries
around the world are attending the conference jointly sponsored
by the U.S. and Russia. Only ten Arab political delegations
are attending the ministerial conference, which was downgraded
from a summit due to the boycott by a dozen Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
This is the strongest boycott the series of MENA annual
conference, which was initiated in 1994 and meant for developing
Arab-Israeli economic links, has ever faced.
</P>
<P>
Without the presence of many Arab partners, the Doha
conference has had to focus strongly on the overall regional
cooperation rather than to give a political incentive to the
Arab-Israeli economic link.
</P>
<P>
In her speech at the opening ceremony, U.S. Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright called on all Arab countries to join
the regional economic cooperation, saying such a process is "in
the long-term best interests of this region."
</P>
<P>
She also said "increased commerce and investment will
diminish the mistrust" between governments of the region.
</P>
<P>
But this view is in clash with that by those Arab
countries staying away from the three-day Doha conference. They
said no economic cooperation with Israel is possible without
progress in the peace process, believing that the Doha conference
will undermine Arab's collective economic block against Israel and
thus deprive Arabs of bargaining chips in peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Arabs have divided views over the U.S. thinking as some
countries accepted regional cooperation as an impetus, or an
alternative way to push forward the peace process.
</P>
<P>
In his opening address, Qatari Emir Shiekh Hamad Bin
Khalifa al-Thani said the regional economic cooperation "would
ultimately serve the cause of peace and development in the
Middle East and in the interest of its peoples."
</P>
<P>
He said a regional economic cooperation will remain "an
unattainable dream" unless peace is achieved in the region,
but adding that political considerations should not over-ride the
Doha conference.
</P>
<P>
In a move apparently designed to demonstrate U.S. desire to
encourage Arab-Israel cooperation, the signing ceremony of a
Jordan-Israel agreement on establishing an industrial zone was
arranged before the inaugural session of the conference.
</P>
<P>
A Saudi Arabian economist told Xinhua that this conference
is being an American economic show.
</P>
<P>
The Arab countries which sent political delegations are
Jordan, Yemen, Kuwait, Oman, the Comores Islands, Mauritania,
Somalia, Djibouti and Tunisia besides host Qatar. But most of
them are just represented by senior officials.
</P>
<P>
The boycott camp includes Egypt, Saudi Arabia, the United
Arab Emirates and Palestine.
</P>
<P>
Some 850 businessmen and investors from the world are also
attending the conference which is convened by the World
Economic Forum. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971116.0028 </DOCNO>
