<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kinkel: WEU Should Enable Joint Crisis Management </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, November 16 (Xinhua) -- German Foreign Minister Klaus
Kinkel today said that Europe should reshape the Western European
Union (WEU) in such a way that it could enable an effective joint
crisis management in Europe in the future.
</P>
<P>
"Europe must be able to speak with one voice in foreign and
security policies and swiftly and effectively react to crisis
situations. A central role should then be played by the Western
European Union as the military arm of the European Union (EU),"
Kinkel said.
</P>
<P>
"The WEU is the hinge linking the NATO (North Atlantic Treaty
Organization) and the EU. It will enable an effective joint crisis
management in Europe in the future," he added.
</P>
<P>
Kinkel made the statement ahead of a ministerial meeting of the
WEU in the eastern German city of Erfurt on November 17-18.
</P>
<P>
Foreign and defense ministers from 28 European states attending
the meeting are expected to discuss how to transform the WEU,
which was founded in 1948 as a western European defense alliance,
into a pillar within a new European security structure.
</P>
<P>
While Germany and France have been asking for a bigger role for
the WEU, Britain fears that a strengthened WEU would weaken the
NATO.
</P>
<P>
A compromise formula was reached during the EU Amsterdam summit
in June this year, under which the WEU and the EU would cooperate
more closely in the future while the EU would also respect the
duties of member states in the NATO.
</P>
<P>
According to a statement issued by the German Foreign Ministry
today, a declaration to be adopted at the end of the WEU meeting
in Erfurt would implement the plans of the EU summit with a goal
to develop the WEU into "a instrument of European crisis and
conflict management."
</P>
<P>
The statement also said that the Erfurt meeting would pave the
way for progress in the following fields:
</P>
<P>
-- improving the operational interlock between the WEU and the
NATO through increased use of NATO resources in WEU-led
operations;
</P>
<P>
-- concrete steps to improve the institutional linkage of the
EU and the WEU decided by the EU Amsterdam summit; and
</P>
<P>
-- deepened integration of central and eastern European
partners into the WEU.
</P>
<P>
The WEU now has 10 full memebers: Belgium, Britain, France,
Germany, Greece,, Italy, Luxembourg, the Netherlands, Portugal and
Spain, along with three associated members as well as five which
now have observer status.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, it still has 10 associated partner states in central
and eastern Europe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
