<HEADLINE> Qatar's Emir Urges U.S. to Push Forward Mideast Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DOHA, November 16 (Xinhua) -- Emir of Qatar Sheikh Hamad Bin
Khalifa al-Thani today denounced the Israeli intransigent policies
towards the Middle East peace process and called on the United
States to push it forward.
</P>
<P>
This came in a speech by Sheik Hamad at the opening session of
the fourth Middle East and North Africa (MENA) Economic Conference
in Qatari capital Doha.
</P>
<P>
He also called on all peace-loving nations an peoples to do
their best to push forward the peace process in accordance with
the foundations endorsed by the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
The emir of Qatar expressed worry about the stumbling of the
Middle East peace process because of the intransigence of the
Israeli government.
</P>
<P>
"The Israeli government must realize that its attitudes, as
well as its actions which are contrary to both all the agreements
sign by it and the U.N. resolutions, have undermined the peace
process and exposed the region to a danger of unpredictable
dimensions," said Sheikh Hamad.
</P>
<P>
Sheik Hamad pointed out that peace in the Middle East is facing
the greatest challenge, hoping that the U.N. would play a more
active role in establishing an overall peace and achieving
stability and prosperity in the region.
</P>
<P>
Sheikh Hamad said he would not like to give a political form to
the Doha economic conference, which is mainly a completion and
continuation of the previous ones held in Casablanca, Amman and
Cairo.
</P>
<P>
About a dozen Arab countries like Egypt, Saudi Arabia, the
United Arab Emirates and the Palestinian National Authority are
staying away from the gathering in protest against the Israeli
hardline policy towards the Mideast peace.
</P>
<P>
He added that the hosting of the conference by Qatar does not
process from its own interests without those of others, and that
the conference is held with the aim of serving the issues of peace
and development in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
Sheikh Hamad said that to create an even-handed base for
economic cooperation in the Middle East would be a reverie without
a fair, overall and lasting peace in the region.
</P>
<P>
The three-day Doha Economic Conference is participated by
delegations from 66 countries, including 10 Arab ones, 850 foreign
businessmen and some 550 Qatari businessmen, with the aim of
discussing ways of regional and international economic
cooperation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
