<HEADLINE> Yangtze River Belt Enters New Development Stage (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, November 16 (Xinhua) -- Economists attending a recent
seminar on economic and trade cooperation along the Yangtze River
agreed that the Yangtze River Economic belt is emerging as a new
shining star in China's national economic development.
</P>
<P>
The zone covers seven provinces and two cities along the
Yangtze River, China's longest river which stretches over 6,300
kilometers and encompasses a river valley covering 1.8 million
square kilometers.
</P>
<P>
The region's economy has outstripped the national average
growth rate since establishment of the Yangtze River Economic Belt
some six years ago.
</P>
<P>
The belt has attracted foreign investment of 15.5 billion US
dollars in 1996, a figure accounting for 30 percent of the
national total.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai, the economic powerhouse in the zone, had approved
16,000 foreign-funded firms by the first half of this year, with
total contracted investments soaring to 26 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai, which is once again working to reestablish itself as
an international financial center, has established a relatively
complete system centered on securities, foreign exchanges and
interbank transactions.
</P>
<P>
Forty-eight of the world's top 50 banks have opened branches in
Shanghai. In 1996, the central government granted approval for
nine foreign banks to handle Renminbi transactions on trial basis.
</P>
<P>
The city's gross domestic product has grown by average annual
rate of 13 percent over the past five years.
</P>
<P>
Establishment of the Pudong New Area in Shanghai represented an
important event promoting economic growth in the Yangtze River
Belt.
</P>
<P>
Pudong has also established specialized markets for 3,000
products, including tobacco, steel, coal, oil and cereals, high
technology, real estate and automobiles. Over 5,000 foreign-funded
firms, 38 foreign banks and 81 trade companies from 24 provinces
and cities have established operations in the area.
</P>
<P>
Pudong's industrial output value for the first three quarters
of this year surged 18 percent to 97.4 billion yuan, with exports
growing by 20 percent monthly since the beginning of this
year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
