<DOCNO> XIE19971116.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yangtze River Belt Enters New Development Stage (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Development in Pudong and the whole of Shanghai has added
impetus to economic growth in surrounding areas. with major
beneficiaries being Jiangsu and Zhejiang provinces.
</P>
<P>
Jiangsu in 1996 attracted 5.5 billion US dollars in foreign
investment. The coastal province's GDP has increased two-fold,
with its exports rising form three billion to 11 billion US
dollars over the past five years.
</P>
<P>
While Zhejiang Province attracted a mere 140 million US dollars
from abroad in 1991, the figure climbed to 1.6 billion US dollars
in 1996. In addition, the province's GDP has grown by 19 percent
annually in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Hubei Province, located in the middle reaches of the Yangtze
River, had approved 6,000 foreign-funded firms through the end of
August this year, with total foreign investments standing at 3.4
billion US dollars. The province's foreign trade volume has
witnessed a year-on-year growth of 17 percent, with economic
growth rate averaging 10 percent over the past five years.
</P>
<P>
Chongqing, a leading industrial center in the upper reaches of
the river, has been in the limelight since it became China's
fourth municipality earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
A Japanese delegation of industrialists, bankers and experts
recently visited Chongqing on a fact-finding tour. Fifty-three
Japanese companies and their Chinese counterparts negotiated a
contract for construction of a container dock on the Yangtze. They
also explored possibilities for reducing pollution and developing
agriculture and animal husbandry in the Yangtze River belt.
</P>
<P>
A number of major transnational companies and financial
institutions such as Sumitomo Bank from Japan and German-based
Siemens have opened representative offices in Chongqing, a city
forged which has economic and trade contacts in 140 countries and
regions.
</P>
<P>
Four comprehensive industrial centers are currently operating
in Shanghai, Nanjing, Wuhan and Chongqing, leading cities along
the river.  
</P>
</TEXT>
