<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hainan Effectively Protects Wetlands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, November 16 (Xinhua) -- The Dongzhaigang Mangrove
Forest Nature Reserve, located in the city of Qiongshan and the
only state wetlands reserve in south China's Hainan Province, is
benefiting from a comprehensive state protection program.
</P>
<P>
The reserve is one of the seven wetlands in the country that
are listed on the register of the International Wetlands
Organization.
</P>
<P>
Wetlands, which are natural ecosystems with various species of
flora and fauna, are noted for their great capacity to purge
sewage and conserve water, according to experts. Wetlands are thus
ideal nature reserves and habitats for many rare species of wild
plants and waterfowl.
</P>
<P>
The reserve, covering about 3,500 hectares, was placed under
state protection in 1986. Since then, the area and breeds of
mangrove forest have been continuously increasing, with more than
2,000 hectares of mangrove forests at present. It amasses 11
families and 18 varieties of mangrove and is the most
well-preserved vegetative cover of its kind in China.
</P>
<P>
The reserve is home to a wide variety of precious plants and
bird species, and is the winter residence for thousands of
migratory birds, according to an official from the local
environmental resources bureau.
</P>
<P>
The city of Qiongshan has established a special committee and
allocated funding to protect the reserve. Local governments at all
levels have also taken part by reminding people to cherish the
natural environment and protect wild animals and plants.
</P>
<P>
The Dongzhaigang Nature Reserve is a national and international
base for scientific research, and also a tourist attraction which
attracts more than 100,000 visitors from home and abroad
annually. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971116.0041 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka Urged to Further Improve Investment Climate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, November 16 (Xinhua) -- Japanese investors have called
on the Bangladeshi authorities to further improve investment
climate and solve their genuine problems to help promote foreign
direct investment in the country, the national news agency BSS
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The call was made here this afternoon at a meeting organized by
the Japan Desk of Bangladesh's Board of Investment (BOI). The aim
of the meeting was to discuss different problems related to the
promotion of Japanese investment in the country.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese investors called for improvement of
administration, infrastructure and financial sector particularly
the foreign exchange operations and commercial banking.
</P>
<P>
They also called for further strengthening of the BOI and the
Bangladesh Export Processing Zone Authority (BEPZA) and improve
conditions for living of foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
BEPZA representatives informed the meeting that about 27,000
square meters of space were still vacant in Chittagong and Dhaka
export processing zones for setting up factories or industrial
units.
</P>
<P>
This is the second meeting with the Japanese investors within a
year, and the meeting decided to have similar discussions within
six months.
</P>
<P>
At present, 71 Japanese companies have registered with the BOI
with an investment capital of nearly 800 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
