<HEADLINE> Industrial Restructuring Brings Hope to Old Northeastern City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, November 16 (Xinhua) -- The industrial sector in
Changchun, a traditional northeastern China industrial center and
the capital of Jilin Province, began to turn a profit in the third
quarter of 1997.
</P>
<P>
The city's slack economy started to pick up in March. In the
first eight months, industrial enterprises had 2.28 billion yuan
(274 million U.S. dollars) in pre-tax profits, a 30 percent
increase over the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
They pocketed a combined net profit of 41 million yuan, 2.2
times the figure of the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Mayor Song Chunhua attributed the achievement to an industrial
restructuring of large and medium-sized state enterprises that
used to be debt-ridden and top heavy with employees.
</P>
<P>
Known as "the Cradle of China's Automotive Industry," Changchun
aims to raise more funds for industrial upgrading by renovating
key state-run companies.
</P>
<P>
Beginning this year, 15 automobile manufacturers have been
undergoing restructuring with 500 million yuan worth of debts
cleared, 15,000 laid-off workers employed, 970 million yuan of
idle state assets reinvested, 960,000 square meters of land and
530,000 square meters of workshops allocated to other uses.
</P>
<P>
Changchun will depend on 30 major enterprises engaged in
producing high-speed trains, cars, tractors and light motorcycles
to increase market share. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
