<HEADLINE> Aircraft Makers Compete for Gulf Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DUBAI, November 16 (Xinhua) -- The world's jet manufacturers
had another chance here today to display on the spot their
latest products to the Gulf region which was believed to be a
tremendous aircraft market.
</P>
<P>
With the opening of the Dubai air show this morning, civil
plane makers were able to fly their flags at the event to fight
for a share of the limelight in the hungry market which was
expected to need thousands of planes by the turn of this century.
</P>
<P>
Military jet providers also got opportunities to become at
the aerospace show an eye-catching exhibitor for buyers,
especially for the host, the United Arab Emirates (UAE), the
biggest customer who is seeking 80 combat planes to beef up its
airforce.
</P>
<P>
Organizers said 500 exhibitors from 31 countries will display
more than 70 planes and introduce maintenance services in the
exhibition village covering an area of more than 30,000 square
meters.
</P>
<P>
Among the exhibitors, aircraft industry giants Boeing and
Airbus Industries are considered to be two tough competitors at
the five-day event, one of the world's three largest after
Britain's Farnborough and the Paris air show.
</P>
<P>
Airbus today introduced its new product A330-220 which is
seen for the first time at a major air show while Boeing joined
the contest with its advanced 777-300.
</P>
<P>
While civil plane makers are fiercely contesting, military
aircraft manufacturers -- including firms from the United States,
Britain, France and Russia -- are also busy in displaying their
latest hardware.
</P>
<P>
Organizers said that apart from big names, the air exhibition
also fielded a substantial number of small and medium suppliers
of a broad scope ranging from aviation maintenance and charter
suppliers. They expected some 30,000 visitors to the air show.
</P>
</TEXT>
