<HEADLINE> Iran Seizes Over 4 Tonnes of Opium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, November 16 (Xinhua) -- The Iranian security forces
seized over 4,000 kilograms of opium in two separate armed
encounters with the smugglers in northeastern province of Khorasan
in the past three days.
</P>
<P>
According to the Iranian official news agency IRNA today,
commander of provincial security forces Brigadier General Bahram
Noruzi said that 2,075 kilograms of opium were caught in the
border area of Khavaf in an operation.
</P>
<P>
Noruzi said that similar operations were launched by the
security forces in the cities of Torbat Jam, Sarakhs and the
provincial capital Mashhad, seizing 2,000 kilograms of opium from
the smugglers.
</P>
<P>
He said that in these operations three smugglers were
arrested with two vehicles, adding that the estimated value of
the drugs seized was about 2,770 million Rials (about 0.9
million dollars).
</P>
<P>
Iran passed a strict anti-drug law in 1989, which empowered
the Iranian authorities to execute any drug trafficker who was
caught with more than 30 grams of heroin or 5,000 grams of
opium.
</P>
<P>
The State Expediency Council ratified an amended law Saturday
to speed up the country's campaign against narcotic-related crimes
by imposing heavy labor punishment for the drug traffickers and
addicts.
</P>
<P>
Iran seized 175 tons of narcotics and arrested 12,000 drug
traffickers during last Iranian calendar year ending March 20,
1997.
</P>
<P>
However, drug trafficking is still one the main social
problems for the Iranian government since the country is one
of the major transit routes for drugs coming from the "Golden
Crescent" on the border area between Pakistan and Afghanistan
destined for Europe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
