<HEADLINE> Iran's Defense Minister Leaves For Visit to UAE </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, November 16 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Defense Minister
Admiral Ali Shamkhani left here for the United Arab Emirates
(UAE) today to attend the international air show in Dubai.
</P>
<P>
Before his departure, Shamkhani told the Iranian official
news agency IRNA that he would hold talks with UAE military
officials about military cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
He said that exchange of military delegations with the
regional countries would pave the way for expansion of defense
cooperation and boost understanding in the region.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian Minister stated that Iran's defense policy is
based on expansion of friendly ties with Islamic countries,
those in the Persian Gulf in particular.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the positive response of the Gulf states
towards the "friendly message" of the Iranian new government,
Shamkhani said the enthusiasm shown by the friendly countries of
the region towards Iran's new initiatives would open bright
prospects for shaping new regional arrangements in the Persian
Gulf.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi made a
"confidence-building mission" tour to the six Gulf nations last
 week, reiterating Iran's foreign policy of building trust and
seeking friendly cooperation among the regional countries.
</P>
<P>
Following Kharrazi's visit, the UAE Defense Minister Sheikh
Mohammad bin Rashid al-Maktoum Saturday called on the Gulf
states to open talks with Iran to improve ties strained by
territorial disputes.
</P>
<P>
"We in the Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) should keep the door
of a dialog, understanding and cooperation with Iran open to
preserve our mutual interests and strengthen our historic
relations," he said.
</P>
<P>
Iran and the UAE have a dispute over the sovereignty of the
three islands of the Abu Musa, the greater and lesser Tumbs at
the mouth of the Hormoz Strait.
</P>
<P>
Iran took over the islands in 1972 after the British colonist
forces withdrew from the region and reached an agreement with the
UAE to co-rule the islands.
</P>
<P>
However, both the countries claim full sovereignty over the
islands and talks during the past years failed to solve their
dispute. 
</P>
</TEXT>
