<HEADLINE> Albright Criticizes Promise-Breaching in Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DOHA, November 16 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright today criticized Middle East regional leaders
for not fulfilling their commitment to the peace process, in an
apparently particular reference to Israel.
</P>
<P>
Albright's address to the opening session of the fourth
Middle East and North Africa economic conference here was
interupted by applause for three times when she made remarks
considered as favoring Arabs in the context of the Mideast peace
process as against Israel.
</P>
<P>
She said that "the peace process is in danger....because
leaders have failed to take the actions required to realize the
possibilities of peace."
</P>
<P>
During the past two days, Albright has met Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu in London and President of
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) Yasser Arafat on resuming
the deadlocked peace process.
</P>
<P>
These meetings have helped bring the parties back to the
negotiation table, she said, describing the talks as serious.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the Israeli-PNA talks had failed to achieve tangible
results following a seven-month stalemate triggered off by
Israeli construction of a Jewish settlement in Arab East
Jerusalem in March.
</P>
<P>
She said her country will continue to play the role of a
honest broker, reiterating that the U.S. objective is to ensure a
comprehensive peace, including the land-for-peace principle.
</P>
<P>
This remark won applause from Arab delegations, whose
countries have complained of Washington's biased Mideast policy
in favor of Israel.
</P>
<P>
She called on both Israeli and Palestinian sides to take
measures for reaching agreements on peace.
</P>
<P>
"Palestinian leaders must intensify cooperation on security
and speak more consistently the language of peace," and "Israeli
leaders must meet their responsibilities by taking steps to
restore Palestinian and Arab confidence in their commitment to
implementing Oslo (peace accords)," she said.
</P>
<P>
Albright made an appeal to all Arab countries to join the
regional economic cooperation that involves Israel, saying "it
will be very helpful to the peace process if all the leaders of
this region can keep the commitment they have made."
</P>
<P>
About half of the Arab countries have not sent their
political delegations to the conference in protest against Israeli
hard-line policy towards peace. They also said Arab-Israel
economic cooperation cannot take off unless progress is made in
the peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
