<HEADLINE> Century-Old Liquor Unearthed in Shenyang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, November 16 (Xinhua) -- More than four tons of liquor
produced more than 150 years ago was unearthed recently from a
cave in Jinzhou in northeast China's Liaoning Province.
</P>
<P>
The century-old spirits, made of red sorghum and millet, have
been approved by the government departments concerned to be sold
on the domestic market by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
A 50-gram bottle of the original spirits will be sold at around
1,500 yuan (180 US dollars). Buyers will also receive a
gold-plated commemorative coin and a commemorative card.
</P>
<P>
Chinese wine-making experts and archaeologists agreed that the
yellow-colored drink was made by a special brewery as a tribute to
the palace. The experts said the liquor is safe to drink.
</P>
<P>
The brewery was the predecessor of the present Lingchuan
Brewery, from where the ancient spirit was discovered. The ancient
brew was sealed for safekeeping in 1845. 
</P>
</TEXT>
