<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2ndlead: MENA Conference Opens Despite Boycott </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DOHA, November 16 (Xinhua) -- The controversial Middle East
and North Africa (MENA) economic conference opened here today
despite an extensive boycott by Arab countries against Israelis'
participation.
</P>
<P>
The opening ceremony was also marked by criticism of Israeli
hard-line policy towards the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Some 2,000 delegates, mostly businessmen from 66 countries
around the world, attended the opening ceremony of the three-day
conference.
</P>
<P>
Ten Arab political delegations are attending the conference,
which was downgraded from a summit to ministerial level.
</P>
<P>
About a dozen Arab countries like Egypt, Saudi Arabia, the
United Arab Emirates and the Palestinian National Authority are
staying away from the gathering in protest against the Israeli
hard-line policy towards the Mideast peace.
</P>
<P>
This is the strongest boycott the series of MENA annual
conference, which was initiated in 1994 and meant for developing
Arab-Israeli economic links, has ever faced.
</P>
<P>
In his opening address, Qatari Emir Sheikh Hamad Bin Khalifa
al-Thani noted that the Doha conference is being convened at a
difficult time when Israel's intransigence stalemated the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
He also said that a regional economic cooperation will remain
"an unattainable dream" unless peace is achieved in the region.
</P>
<P>
But he added that political considerations should not
over-ride the Doha conference.
</P>
<P>
Without the presence of many Arab partners, the conference
will have to focus strongly on the overall regional cooperation
rather than to give a political boost to the Arab-Israeli
economic link, observers said.
</P>
<P>
In her speech to the opening session, U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright stressed the significance of the regional
economic cooperation to the peace process, saying such efforts
will be in the long-term best interests of this region.
</P>
<P>
The U.S., a co-sponsor of the Doha conference together with
Russia, has been trying hard to divorce political influence from
the economic conference, while many Arab countries only condition
their business links with Israel on progress in the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
But in an apparent reference to Israel, Albright accused some
regional leaders of failing to keep their commitments to peace.
</P>
<P>
Some 850 businessmen and investors from around the world are
also attending the conference. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971116.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Li Peng Returns From Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 16 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Li Peng
returned to Beijing this evening following an official goodwill
visit to Japan which started on November 11.
</P>
<P>
Dignitaries greeting Li in the Great Hall of the People
included vice-premiers Zhu Rongji, Zou Jiahua, Qian Qichen, Li
Lanqing, Wu Bangguo and Jiang Chunyun, as well as Wang Bingqian,
vice-chairman of the Standing Committee of the National People's
Congress, Luo Gan, state councillor and secretary-general of the
State Council, and Zhu Guangya, vice-chairman of the National
Committee of the Chinese People's Political Consultative
Conference.
</P>
<P>
The charge d'affaires ad interim of the Japanese Embassy in
China, Yuji Miyamoto, was also present at the Great Hall of the
People to greet the Chinese premier.
</P>
<P>
Members of Li's entourage who returned here aboard the same
plane included Li's wife Zhu Lin, State Councillor and Minister of
the State Science and Technology Commission Song Jian, Deputy
Secretary-General of the State Council He Chunlin, Minister of
Electronics Industry Hu Qili, Director of the Research Office of
the State Council Wang Mengkui, Vice-Foreign Minister Tang
Jiaxuan, and Long Yongtu, chief negotiator of the Ministry of
Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation. 
