<DOCNO> XIE19971116.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hungary Holds Referendum on NATO Membership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, November 16 (Xinhua) -- Hungarians today took to
10,582 polling stations to decide if their country should join the
North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
Hungarian President Arpad Goncz called the referendum, which
began at 6 a.m. local time (0500 GMT), a "historic chance for
Hungarians to decide their own future."
</P>
<P>
On his part, Prime Minister Gyula Horn said he would consider
it a "major success" if 60-65 percent of the 8 million eligible
voters show up before 7 p.m. (1800 GMT).
</P>
<P>
Its result, expected 11 p.m. (2200 GMT), would be valid if
either the turnout is over 50 percent, or at least 2 million
voters are for or against NATO entry.
</P>
<P>
The referendum was decided in the 1994 general election, when
the Socialists promised to let the people have their say on
joining the Western military alliance.
</P>
<P>
Hungary, the Czech Republic and Poland are expected to become
the first countries from the former Warsaw Pact to be accepted by
an expanded NATO in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Of the three countries, only Hungary chose to hold a referendum
on this matter, although all of its parliamentary parties are
known to prefer the NATO bid.
</P>
<P>
The most prominent groups against the move are the Workers'
Party and Alba Circle, who allege that NATO membership would be
both expensive and unnecessary. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
