<DOCNO> XIE19971116.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cuba Outlasts China at World Grand Champions Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OSAKA, Japan, November 16 (Xinhua) -- Olympic and world
champion Cuba Sunday outlasted China 3-2 in a repeat of last
year's Olympic final and remained unbeaten after women's tow
rounds competition at the world volleyball grand champions cup.
</P>
<P>
Cuba rallied from two sets down to score a 9-15, 11-15, 15-7,
15-8, 15-10 victory in the almost two hours play.
</P>
<P>
Two leg injuries on starting seter Zhu Yunying and spiker Wang
Ziling cost China the chance to get its revenge against Cuba for
the Olympic defeat in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
China clincked the first two sets with quick attackings and
better rhythm, which also giving them a 6-3 lead in the third set
when Zhu Yunying twisted her left knee and was sidelined on the
bench.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese pace suddenly sank into a mass after Zhu's injury
while Cuba took the chance to grab seven points in a row and
outscored China 12-1 in the rest of the set.
</P>
<P>
China lost its last chance since Wang Ziling, who socred the
team's third most points of 12, hurt her left ankle when the
Chinese trailed only 9-10 in the deciding set, which applided a
rally-point system in the tournament.
</P>
<P>
"It was always tough to play against China and today we were
little bit lucker to win the match," said Antonio Perdomo, head
coach of Cuba.
</P>
<P>
European champion Russia also kept unbeaten after outsmashing
the tough resisting Japanese squad 3-0 earlier Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The tall and stronger Russian spikers, a 3-0 winner over Asian
champion China on Friday, took a 15-3, 15-7, 27-25 win over the
host.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese girls showed no sign of giving up and surprised
their opponents by jumping to 5-1 and 9-6 lead in the third set.
</P>
<P>
However, Japan with the size disadvantage soon watched its lead
slip away after a ferocious over-block attcking effort by Russia,
who cut the gap to 12-13 when the 25-minute exceeded.
</P>
<P>
According to the new rule introduced in the tournament, when
any of the first four sets is not completed within 25-minute, the
scoring system will be changed from sevice-point to rally-point.
</P>
<P>
The change of rule really thrilled 6,000 young fans at the
OSAKA Jo Hall when the two teams fought neck to neck for the
2-point lead necessary to win the tie-break and the set.
</P>
<P>
Finally, with harder smashes and blocks, Russian held down
Japanese 27-25, the hightest point in a set ever scored since the
tournament started Friday.
</P>
<P>
In Sunday's first game, Brazil edged South Korea 16-14 after
the 25-minute rule was applied. The taller Brazilian team then run
away with 15-4, 15-3 in the following sets.
</P>
<P>
"As our national league tournament had just finished, our
players are too tired to meet my demands with their mental
concentration," South Korea coach Kim Hyung-Sil said.
</P>
<P>
The women spikers of the six participating teams will move to
Hiroshima on Monday and play their third round before heading on
to Tokyo for the rest two rounds matches. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
