<HEADLINE> Child Education Vexing Chinese Urbanites </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, November 16 (Xinhua) -- Children's education has
become a vexatious problem for Chinese urban dwellers, more
pressing than unemployment and the cost of living, a recent survey
has shown.
</P>
<P>
A survey of 1,524 people in the cities of Beijing, Shanghai,
Guangzhou, Xiamen, and Chongqing showed that Chinese are worrying
about education, employment, income, health, their careers, the
performance of their companies, getting laid off, social security,
housing, and the cost of living.
</P>
<P>
But, above 18 percent of those responding said that they worry
about their children's education most, and a third of these are
not satisfied with their children's education.
</P>
<P>
Other parents worry about their children's future and their
behavior. Some think their children are too dependent on their
parents and lack a sense of responsibility.
</P>
<P>
The survey also showed that while workers worry about their
company's future, the managers think their workers suffer from a
lack of enterprise and ability.
</P>
<P>
Half of the respondents say they worry about pensions and
health care for senior citizens. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
