<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, November 16 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
held talks today with visiting Palestinian National Authority
President Yasser Arafat on the latest developments of the Mideast
peace process and the outcome of recent U.S. mediation efforts.
</P>
<P>
Arafat arrived here this morning on a several hours' visit to
Egypt from Bern, Switzerland, where he met with U.S. Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright Saturday to reactivate the faltering
peace drive.
</P>
<P>
Upon his arrival, Arafat said they will explore means of
pushing forward the staggering Mideast peace process and the
outcome of his talks with Albright.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa and Saeb Erekat,
Palestinian Minister of Local Government, and other top aides from
both sides attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, Albright confirmed that her meeting with Arafat in
Bern and with Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu in London
Friday unveiled a breakthrough in the peace-making process,
expressing hope that this breakthrough would be materialized
before the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
Albright said that she conveyed urgent messages to Arafat and
Netanyahu necessitating the resumption of Israeli-Palestinian
negotiations that came to a halt since March due to Israel's
construction of new Jewish settlements on occupied Palestinian
lands. 
</P>
