<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Review on Bombay Stock Exchange </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, November 16 (Xinhua) -- Share prices plunged on the
Bombay Stock Exchange (BSE) during the week in the wake of heavy
selling pressure by foreign institutional investors which was
induced by fresh speculation of an imminent rupee devaluation.
</P>
<P>
The BSE sensitive index would have fallen further substantially
but for the timely support by financial institutions, who extended
all-round support to arrest downward trend on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The sentiment was affected adversely by the various negative
factors like uncertain political situation in India, unstable
Asian stocks and lack of the government's initiatives for the
revival of the capital market.
</P>
<P>
Foreign institutional investors were selling heavily in several
blue chip scrips in a bid to square off their positions ahead of
the year end in view of these negative factors.
</P>
<P>
The lack of confidence among investors due to persistent fall
in share prices, reflecting a loss of over 536 points in the last
four weeks, was another reason for the depressed conditions.
</P>
<P>
The BSE sensitive index dropped by 177.55 points to end the
week at 3,569.77 as against last weekend close of 3,747.32. The
BSE-100 index also tumbled by 75.18 to close the week at 1,544.03
from previous weekend close of 1,619.21.
</P>
<P>
The BSE-200 and the Dollex were quoted substantially down at
347.16 and 157.36 at the weekend compared with last weekend close
of 364.31 and 165.95 respectively.
</P>
<P>
The volume of business was remained very low at 30.03 billion
rupees (822.7 million U.S. dollars), fractionally down from last
week turnover of 30.63 billion rupees (839.2 million dollars).
</P>
