<DOCNO> XIE19971116.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepal Introduces Value Added Tax </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, November 16 (Xinhua) -- The government of Nepal
today formally introduced the value added tax (VAT) as scheduled
despite strong opposition from the business community.
</P>
<P>
Early in 1993, the VAT system was developed for Nepal by the
United States Agency for International Development and the Harvard
International Industrial Development Institute.
</P>
<P>
A VAT act was passed in Nepal in 1995, which has a provision of
one hundred percent penalty and maximum imprisonment of six months
for those who evade tax by declining to register on the VAT.
</P>
<P>
The government of Nepal favors this tax system, which broadens
the tax net and allows the government to collect more revenues.
</P>
<P>
Nepali newspapers quoted government officials as saying that
the VAT has become both a compulsion to meet the commitment by the
government to the donor agencies for tax reform and a necessity to
increase the contribution of tax revenue which is only about 11
percent of the GDP, one of the lowest in the world.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said another strong reason is the pressing imperative
of liberalizing international trade with tariffs dwindling
worldwide, especially in India, Nepal's major trading partner.
</P>
<P>
But the business community argues that the VAT is inflationary,
encourages smuggling across the border and does not work in a
market like Nepal's where account keeping is very low.
</P>
<P>
In the past three years, the two sides held several rounds of
meeting but reached no agreement.
</P>
<P>
The VAT is not an additional tax, but will be levied in place
of the existing sales tax, contract tax, entertainment tax and
hotel tax.
</P>
<P>
The VAT, first introduced in France in 1954, has been adopted
by about 110 countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
