<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Unfolds Step to Check Illegal Mining </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, November 16 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria is to set up mineral
mines offices all over the country as a new step to curtail
illegal mining.
</P>
<P>
Anyone caught and proved to be illegal miners would be
prosecuted, said Minister of Solid Minerals Development Alhaji
Kaloma Ali, quoted by the official newspaper New Nigerian today.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria boasts rich mineral resources. Of the 450 proven
minerals including gold, coal, alumimium and iron ore, 33
varieties are ready for exploitation and utilization, according
to the ministry.
</P>
<P>
The ministry was established in March 1995 in an effort to
make use of the rich resources.
</P>
<P>
The development of minieral resources is also part of the
government strategy to reduce the country's overdependence on
crude oil, the mainstay industry whose export earns more than 80
percent of the country's foreign exchange.
</P>
<P>
But illegal mining has increasingly become an underminer for
the development of the industry.
</P>
<P>
To create an environment for massive investment into the solid
minerals sector, the ministry has reviewed all the laws and
regulations passed during the colonial days to conform with
international standards on mining policies, according to the
minister.
</P>
<P>
The review of the obsolete Minerals Acts, the formation of a
new Nigerian Minerals Policy, the Nigerian minerals appraisals
and monetization programs as well as the ban on importation of
certain minerals were all part of the efforts, he said.
</P>
<P>
Solid minerals whose importation is banned by the government
include gypsum, kaolin and barite.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, the government policy is to produce
as many as possible industrial minerals in the country so that
industries will utilize them.
</P>
<P>
Genuine industrialists would be assisted by giving them
necessary incentives such tax relief, tax holiday etc., he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
