<HEADLINE> Italian Euro-tax to Be Returned in Tax Credits in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, November 15 (Xinhua) -- The Euro-tax, a one-off levy
collected earlier this year to ensure Italy's place in the
European economic and monetary union, may be paid back in the form
of a deduction from income tax declarations, the Government said
here today.
</P>
<P>
In an interview on the national radio, Italian Finance Ministry
Undersecretary Fausto Vigevano explained that the pay-back will
correspond to the exact amount received from each tax-payer.
</P>
<P>
Italian Prim Minister Romano Prodi announced Friday that in
1999 tax-payers would get back up to 60 percent of what they paid
in Euro-tax.
</P>
<P>
"The payments made can be considered as tax credits, so when
people declare their income and pay the first tax installment,
they can deduct the amount of Euro-tax they are entitled to get
back," Vigevano said.
</P>
<P>
He added that it was no yet certain whether the Euro-tax would
be paid back via tax declarations in 1999, or via declarations
afterwards concerning income of that year.
</P>
<P>
The Italian government imposed the tax earlier this year as a
measure to help bring public finances into line with the
parameters for the EMU and the singly currency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
