During his stay in Tokyo, Li held talks with Japanese Prime
Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto on strengthening bilateral ties, paid a
courtesy call to Emperor Akihito and met Japanese government officials
and business leaders.
</P>
<P>
When bidding farewell to Hashimoto before leaving Tokyo to visit
other cities, the Chinese premier expressed satisfaction with his
visit to Japan, while Hashimoto hailed the visit as a success.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto said Li's visit will further friendly relations and
encourage cooperation between Japan and China.
</P>
<P>
Li and his entourage then toured Nagoya, Osaka and Nara, visiting a
number of leading Japanese car and electronic manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
Li's entourage includes his wife Zhu Lin, State Councillor and
Minister in charge of the State Science and Technology Commission Song
Jian, Deputy Secretary-General of the State Council He Chunlin,
Minister of Electronics Industry Hu Qili, Director of the Research
Office of the State Council Wang Mengkui, Vice-Foreign Minister Tang
Jiaxuan, Chairman of the China Council for the Promotion of
International Trade Yu Xiaosong, and Chief Negotiator of the Ministry
of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation Long Yongtu.
</P>
<P>
On the last day of his visit to Japan, Li and his party visited
Toshodaiji, a Buddhist monastery in the ancient capital of Nara,
founded by Jianzhen, a Chinese monk in the eighth century.
</P>
<P>
At a luncheon given in his honor afterwards in a hotel in Nara by
Nara Governor Yoshiya Kakimoto, Li said he was honored to have been
able to visit a temple founded by Jianzhen who devoted himself to
fostering friendly ties between China and Japan.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese premier expressed the hope that the two neighboring
countries will continue to jointly prosper in the future.
</P>
<P>
At the Kansai airport, Li and his entourage were seen off by
Osaka Governor Nokku Yokoyama, Japanese ambassador to China
Yoshiyasu Sato, Chinese ambassador to Japan Xun Dunxin and other
Japanese government officials. 
