<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1stlead: MENA Conference Opens Despite Boycott </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DOHA, November 16 (Xinhua) -- The controversial Middle East
and North Africa (MENA) economic conference opened here today
despite an extensive boycott by Arab countries against Israelis'
participation.
</P>
<P>
The opening ceremony of the three-day conference was attended
by some 2,000 delegates, mostly businessmen from 66 countries
around the world.
</P>
<P>
Ten Arab political delegations are attending the conference,
which was downgraded from a summit to ministerial level.
</P>
<P>
About a dozen Arab countries like Egypt, Saudi Arabia, the
United Arab Emirates and the Palestinian National Authority are
staying away from the gathering in protest against the Israeli
hard line policy toward the Mideast peace.
</P>
<P>
This is the strongest boycott the series of MENA annual
conference, which was initiated in 1994 and meant for developing
Arab-Israeli economic links, has ever faced.
</P>
<P>
Without the presence of many Arab partners, the conference
will have to focus strongly on the overall regional cooperation
rather than to give a political boost to the Arab-Israeli
economic link, observers said.
</P>
<P>
The United States has tried hard to make the conference a
success. U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright attended the
opening ceremony to show support.
</P>
<P>
Some 850 businessmen and investors from around the world are
also attending the conference. 
</P>
</TEXT>
