<DOCNO> XIE19971116.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan, Israel Agree to Establish Industrial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DOHA, November 16 (Xinhua) -- Jordan and Israel signed a
U.S.-backed agreement to establish a joint industrial zone on
the sidelines of the Doha Arab-Israel economic conference which
faces a widespread Arab boycott.
</P>
<P>
Jordan is one of the few Arab countries doing business with
Israel, while many Arab countries are imposing a collective
economic block against Israel in protest against its hardline
policy blamed for bogging down the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The project has been prepared with the full support of the
United States. U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and
Secretary of Commerce William Daley attended the signing
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
In her speech, Albright described the project as "a model
cooperation (between an Arab country and Israel) for others to
follow."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. holds that the Israel-Arab economic cooperation
serves to boost the stalled Middle East peace process, a stance
favored by the Israelis.
</P>
<P>
Albright also said the project is a "milestone" brought about
by the peace process, adding that "positive result from peace
process still can be felt."
</P>
<P>
The support for the project reflects the U.S. commitment to
the partners in the peace process, she said.
</P>
<P>
The Irbid Qualifying Industrial Zone will cover an area of
200 hectares. The project itself won't cost any investment
input, Israeli Minister of Industry and Trade Natan Sharansky
explained to Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
The products in the zone can enter the U.S. market with a
duty-free entry. But this benefit is available to Egypt, Israel
and Jordan only.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed by Sharansky and his Jordanian
counterpart Hani Moulki. They also expressed the hope that such a
Jordan-Israel cooperation will be expanded to other areas in
the future.
</P>
<P>
Jordan is one of the only two Arab countries which have signed
peace agreements with Israel, and it has reached agreements with
Israel on a number of big projects.
</P>
<P>
An Saudi Arabian economist attending the conference told
Xinhua that Jordan's signing of the industrial zone agreement
would be viewed by many Arabs as an action of "revolt."
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed just before the opening of the
Middle East and North Africa economic conference which is meant
to boost regional economic cooperation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
