<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Solid Foundations Laid for Sino-S. African Trade Coop: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(by Liu Yegang Zhao Yi)
</P>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, November 16 (Xinhua) -- A senior Chinese
official said today that the visit by a Chinese trade and
economic delegation to South Africa has achieved positive
achievements and paved the way for further cooperation between
the two countries after the establishment of diplomatic
relations.
</P>
<P>
The 11-day tour is a great success, Shi Guangsheng, head of
the Chinese delegation told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
The delegation, which ended its visit this morning, met with
South African National Assembly Speaker Frene Ginwala, Foreign
Minister Alfred Nzo and some other cabinet members during its
stay in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Shi said his team also held "in-depth, extensive, fruitful and
constructive" talks with South African Trade and Industry
Minister Alec Erwin.
</P>
<P>
The two countries signed 18 trade and investment contracts and
protocols totaling 630 million U.S. dollars, he said.
</P>
<P>
Shi, who is Deputy Minister of Foreign Trade and Economic
Cooperation, said business circles of the two countries had
established channels of contact and enhanced mutual understanding
through meetings, visits and exchange of views.
</P>
<P>
Bilateral trade and economic cooperation have been growing at
a rapid speed, Shi said.
</P>
<P>
Bilateral trade reached 1.35 billion U.S. dollars in 1996 from
a poor base of 14.65 million dollars in 1992.
</P>
<P>
He said China is speeding up investment in South Africa and
more than 50 Chinese enterprises have pumped over 100 million
dollars in the country.
</P>
<P>
Besides, Chinese companies have signed more than 120 labor
contracts in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
He predicted that there is a great potential and bright
prospects for cooperation in the near future since the two
economies are highly complementary.
</P>
<P>
China is willing to promote practicable economic and trade
cooperation in various manners with South Africa on the basis of
equality and mutual benefit and common development, Shi said.
</P>
<P>
Shi believed that with the normalization of relations, the two
countries will expand cooperation and exchange of visits and
information in the fields of space, aviation, telecommunications,
electronics, mining, metallurgy, energy, agriculture, finance,
transport, tourism and architecture.
</P>
<P>
He said the Chinese government encourages investment in South
Africa and at the same time welcomes South African companies to
make their presence in China.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the confidence that China and South Africa are
surely to be able to establish new trade and economic relaitons
geared to the 21st century after the establishment of diplomatic
relations.
</P>
<P>
South African President Nelson Mandela announced in November
last year that his country would sever "diplomatic ties" with
Taiwan and establish full diplomatic relations with the People's
Republic of China at the end of this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
