<HEADLINE> Australian PM Rules Out Sending Troops to Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, November 16 (Xinhua) -- The Australian government
today ruled out sending Australian troops to the Middle East as
tensions between Iraq and the United States continued to rise, the
Australian Associated Press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Australian Prime Minister John Howard told reporters in Sydney
today that Australia would not send troops to join American and
British forces in the Middle East while a diplomatic solution to
the crisis was being sought.
</P>
<P>
Howard was quoted by the new agency as describing the situation
as very tense.
</P>
<P>
"(But) I don't think the question of Australian forces'
involvement arises at this time," he said.
</P>
<P>
But Australian Foreign Minister Alexander Downer told a local
radio program today that Australia would support military action
if there was no diplomatic solution to the crisis.
</P>
<P>
The crisis began last month when Iraq ordered the expulsion of
the U.S. weapons inspectors working for the United Nations on the
ground that the U.S. inspectors are spies, and threatened to fire
on U.S. manned U-2 surveillance aircraft flying over Iraq.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton has reportedly held talks with
British Prime Minister Tony Blair about the question of a military
strike against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Iraq, meanwhile, has reiterated threats to shoot down any
American U-2 planes that fly over the country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
