<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thousands of Kenyan Flood Victims Face Starvation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, November 14 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of people in
coastal Kenya's Tana River District, where all villages have
been submerged after the river burst its banks, are faced with
starvation unless they get emergency food supplies.
</P>
<P>
The district has received no supplies of dry foods, fuel or
medicine since the unprecedented rainfall caused by the El Nino
weather phenomenon struck Coast Province a month ago, local
reports said today.
</P>
<P>
Attempts by the Kenyan government to provide flood victims
with food have been hindered by damaged roads and bridges. An
estimated 60,000 people require assistance, said the reports.
</P>
<P>
Most of the affected region could not be accessed either by
road or sea and the helicopters could not land because the area
was flooded, Minister in the Presidential Office John Koech was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
However, the government will try its best to deliver food,
medicine and fuel supplies there, he said after a one-day tour by
a helicopter to the worst-hit Garsen, Hola and Kipini areas in
the district on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Flood waters from the River Tana have covered two-to-three
kilometer stretches from the banks, leaving more than 25,000
people homeless, estimated 10,000 head of livestock dead and
12,000 hectares of rice paddy destroyed.
</P>
<P>
The river is the country's biggest river fed by major
tributaries from Mount Kenya and eastern Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Essential commodities' prices are skyrocketing there, making
it impossible for most people to afford them.
</P>
<P>
A two-kilogram packet of maize flour is selling at 165
Shillings and a kilogram of sugar 185 Shillings. But the normal
prices are 50 and 45 Shillings respectively (around 63.7
Shillings equal to one U.S. Dollar at present ).
</P>
<P>
There are no beans, cooking fat or other essential foods as
they ran out two weeks ago and no new supplies have been brought
in, said the reports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971116.0106 </DOCNO>
