<HEADLINE> S. African Companies to Open New Int'l Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, November 16 (Xinhua) -- South African companies
investing abroad are switching attention from traditional
locations in Western Europe and North America to Eastern Europe,
South America, Asia-Pacific and Africa, a local daily reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted a public survey as saying that many South
African companies are expected to increase their offshore
investments with Africa emerging as a priority region followed by
Asia-Pacific, Western Europe, North America, South America and
Eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
The survey was based on responses from 47 companies.
</P>
<P>
"Intended countries for investment are even more diverse than
current investment locations, suggesting movement away from
traditional investment countries such as the UK," said the
survey.
</P>
<P>
Establishing a sales presence in these regions was regarded as
a priority by a quarter of respondents, followed by manufacturing
and mining.
</P>
<P>
The average size of investment financing from South African
sources was more than seven million U.S. Dollars, and from
foreign sources was about 5.2 million Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The strongest motivations for international expansion are to
reach new markets and to become internationally competitive, the
survey said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
