<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Unclaimed Baggage Seized by Bangladeshi Customs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, November 16 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi customs officials at
Zia International Airport have seized two pieces of unclaimed
baggage and recovered gold bars, gold ornaments and computer
spares worth around 20 million taka (0.45 million U.S. dollars),
according to the airport resources received here today.
</P>
<P>
Customs officials found the unclaimed baggage at "transit
baggage area" near the customs arrival hall Friday night. The
officials were suspicious of the two pieces of baggage and took
them for scanning, and later they recovered 85 pieces of gold bars
weighing ten grams each, a gold chain weighing about 10,742 grams,
228 pieces of video compact disks and a huge quantity of computer
spares.
</P>
<P>
Price of the seized gold bars and ornaments was estimated at 13
million taka (about 290,000 dollars) while computer spares and
video compact disks at 6.3 million taka (1.41 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
Customs officials said that although the baggage came from
abroad but they were not bearing any tag of international flights.
The baggage were carrying domestic flight tags. There has been no
identification of owner of the baggage, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Seized gold bars and ornaments will be deposited to the central
bank after completing necessary formalities, the sources added.
</P>
</TEXT>
