<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Discusses Diplomatic Solution on Iraq With Allies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 15 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
today telephoned French President Jacques Chirac and the two
agreed on the importance of looking for a diplomatic solution to
the standoff with Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, who is in California to raise funds for his Democratic
Party, and Chirac, who is visiting Vietnam, spoke for 35 minutes,
White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, Clinton called British Prime Minister Tony Blair
to discuss the same issue.
</P>
<P>
"President Chirac agreed on the point that the first priority
is to look for a diplomatic solution," Lockhart said, adding that
the two presidents discussed some ideas about how to get U.N. arms
inspections back on track.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman added that the conversation was "a constructive
exchange of ideas."
</P>
<P>
"The president is continuing his efforts to work with our
allies to try to forge a diplomatic solution to the current
situation," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Following the conversation between Clinton and Blair, a senior
U.S. official said they have agreed to diplomatic solutions in
pressuring Iraqi President Saddam Hussein to reverse course in the
latest arms inspection crisis.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, conferring for about 10 minutes with Blair from Air
Force One while in flight from Las Vegas to Sacramento, discussed
how to maintain unity on the U.N. Security Council in "seeking a
diplomatic solution" to the arms inspection crisis, the official
said.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders agreed to contact other leaders over the next
few days in search of a diplomatic solution that would allow a
resumption of the U.N. weapons inspections in Iraq, he said.
</P>
<P>
The official would not say how long the United States was
willing to pursue a diplomatic solution.
</P>
<P>
"I don't think it would be helpful to put a time frame on it,"
he said. "We want to do this until there is no hope." 
</P>
</TEXT>
