<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NZ First to Stay in Coalition Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, November 16 (Xinhua) -- The New Zealand First Party
has decided to stay within the Coalition Government, meaning it
will support Prime Minister-designate Jenny Shipley.
</P>
<P>
The decision was announced by NZ First leader Winston Peters
this afternoon at the last hour of the party's convention in the
South Island city of Christchurch, Radio NZ reported.
</P>
<P>
Peters said he had assurances from coalition partner the
National Party that there would be a continuation of the coalition
direction and agreement.
</P>
<P>
NZ First decision has ensured that the present government will
continue to rule for the next two years.
</P>
<P>
The decision has been widely expected by observers here. They
said NZ First has no other choice but to stay with National.
</P>
<P>
On Friday night, Peters approached Labor Leader Helen Clark on
the possibility of NZ First supporting a Labor minority
government, but the offer was turned down by Clark, who called for
an early election instead.
</P>
<P>
Observers noted that if the coalition collapses now and a snap
election is held, NZ First will be voted out of politics as its
popularity declined rapidly in the past year. With only two
percent support rate at present, it will not be able to pass the
five percent threshold to have listed MPs in parliament.
</P>
<P>
Today's decision has taken NZ First almost two weeks to make
since Shipley replaced Prime Minister Jim Bolger as the National
Party leader early this month. Peters feared that Shipley's tough
matter would endanger his party's standing in the coalition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971116.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bicycle Sector Pedals Way to Recovery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 16 (Xinhua) -- China's bicycle makers can
finally let up on the brakes as sales are gradually recovering
from a low ebb, according to Today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
Since 1988, the supply of Chinese bicycles started to outstrip
demand, and the situation lasted until now.
</P>
<P>
Starting in 1991, the relevant government department has worked
out ambitious plans and after years of remoulding, the industrial
structure and product mix of China's bicycle industry was improved
and sales started to pick up.
</P>
<P>
Last year, 28 million bicycles were produced. This was a
decrease of 24.2 percent over the previous year. Of these, 25
million were sold on the domestic market.
</P>
<P>
China's domestic market will take in 30 million bicycles this
year, which represents a seven-percent increase over last year, a
China National Council of Light Industry official said.
</P>
<P>
He said as people's living standards rise, the increase in
bicycle sales in the domestic market hinges largely on people
buying a second bicycle, and the cycle of replacement will become
shorter in the future.
</P>
<P>
A huge potential market for bicycles also exists in the
relatively less developed interior areas and the ever burgeoning
countryside. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
