<HEADLINE> Economic News Briefs from Mercosur Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO, November 15 (Xinhua) -- The following are some
economic news briefs from the four Southern Common Market
(Mercosur) countries over the past week.
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- The economy ministers of the Mercosur countries --
Argentina, Brazil, Paraguay and Uruguay, decided here on November
14 to raise by 3 percent their Common External Tariff (AEC) on
imports from outside the bloc.
</P>
<P>
The decision, which will be in force until December 31 of the
year 2000, are subject to the approval of the 13th meeting of the
Common Market Council to be held here in December.
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- The Brazilian government announced on November 10 a
package of fiscal adjustments aimed to achieve an immediate saving
of 20 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The package includes tax increases, the dismissal of 33,000
public employees, restriction on imports, and encouragement for
export.
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- The Interameican Development Bank (IADB) approved
on November 11 two credits totaling 557 million U.S. dollars for
technical and professional training and improving the electric
energy system of Brazil.
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- The Central Bank of Argentina reserves in gold
and international currencies were assessed on November 14 to stand at 20.361
billion dollars, the highest level in the last years.
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO -- Brazil's trade deficit with Argentina
reached 1.3 billion dollars in the first 10 months of this year,
said the Foreign Trade Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The data show that Brazilian exports to Argentina totaled 5.57
billion dollars and imports from Argentina were 6.86 billion
dollars. 
</P>
