<DOCNO> XIE19971116.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Market Access Key to China's Entry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 16 (Xinhua) -- Though China has taken
tremendous pains in the long-running battle to gain accession to
the World Trade Organization (WTO), whether it will soon see its
efforts pay off still hangs in the balance, a senior trade expert
said recently in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The major obstacle to China's entry into WTO still lies with
the market access issues said Xu Xianquan, a researcher with the
Institute of International Trade and Economic Co-operation.
</P>
<P>
On October 1, China slashed tariffs on more than 4,800
commodities, bringing the average tariffs level from 23 percent to
17 percent.
</P>
<P>
And President Jiang Zemin committed to further cutting the
average tariffs to 15 percent by 2000.
</P>
<P>
All these have sufficiently shown China's confidence and
determination to integrate itself into the world market, Xu said.
</P>
<P>
"Nevertheless," he said,"some countries are insatiable,
demanding China immediately reduce its tax rate to eight percent.
</P>
<P>
"Many of China's industries are still in infancy," he said,
"Therefore it is reasonable for China to ask for a transition
period."
</P>
<P>
China also has given its word to open more than 30 sideline
industries such as financial service industry, Xu said.
</P>
<P>
However, despite the sincerity China has shown in its actions
to join WTO, some unreasonable and excessive demands are imposed
on it, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Thirty-three countries, including the European Union as a
whole, have asked to have bilateral talks with China on Market
access.
</P>
<P>
A new round of WTO talks on China's accession will begin next
month in Geneva.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
