<HEADLINE> Foreign Investment Flow Into Ukraine Still Slow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, November 15 (Xinhua) -- The flow of investment into
Ukraine is still slow and unlikely to rise by the end of the year,
a senior Ukrainian official said today.
</P>
<P>
First Deputy Economy Minister Vasyl Shevchuk said the
government has registered 1,369 foreign investments in the first
ten months of 1997.
</P>
<P>
All these investments amount to 328.8 million U.S. dollars.
This brought per capita investment in the Ukrainian economy to 32
U.S. dollars, or a total of more than 1.6 billion dollars since
independence in 1991. This level of investment is far below
Ukraine's eastern European neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Individual investments in the Ukrainian economy remain
small-scale, Shevchuk said, adding that most investors are
entrepreneurs making small investments for quick profits. 
