<HEADLINE> New Plan Guarantees Benefits for Chinese Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 16 (Xinhua) -- The shattering of the State
insurance "iron rice bowl" will not threaten social stability as
feared by some China watchers, a top government official said last
week, according to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
A basic pension, medical and unemployment insurance system will
be in place by the end of the century, said Wang Jianlun, Chinese
Vice-minister of Labour.
</P>
<P>
China so far has accumulated more than 60 billion yuan pension
funds for urban state-owned businesses' employees, according to
the paper.
</P>
<P>
These businesses are required to set up a personal account for
each of the individual employees which equals to 11 percent of
their salaries. Employees pay four percent of their personal
account and the rest is covered by their employers.
</P>
<P>
China has launched a "re-employment project" to help the
unemployed find new jobs, according to Wang.
</P>
<P>
A diversified medical insurance system has also sheltered
people from the risk of major diseases, she said.
</P>
<P>
Wang will discuss pension fund reform with foreign experts in
Manila next week at an international conference.  
</P>
