<HEADLINE> Russia, Japan Decide to Draft Peace Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, November 15 (Xinhua) -- Russian Foreign Minister
Yevgeny Primakov said today Russia and Japan would "effectively
and positively" implement the agreement reached between the two
countries in Krasnoyarsk, eastern Siberia, early this month.
</P>
<P>
However, Primakov said both sides agreed that no hasty steps
would be taken in addressing thorny issues in bilateral relations,
the Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Early this month, Russian President Boris Yeltsin and Japanese
Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto decided at an informal summit in
Krasnoyarsk to make utmost efforts to sign a peace treaty by the
year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Primakov, who returned here Friday after a visit to Japan aimed
at preparing for the Russian-Japanese peace treaty talks, said a
special team consisting of delegates from both sides is expected
to start drafting a peace treaty next January.
</P>
<P>
Russian Deputy Foreign Minister Grigory Karasin and Japanese
Vice Foreign Minister Muhopy Tamoa will meet in Moscow soon to
decide on the members of the special team, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Primakov said that the trust between Russia and Japan is
increasing and both sides have reached agreement on a series of
economic issues and Yeltsin's visit to Japan next April.
</P>
<P>
Russia and Japan have not yet signed a peace treaty for more
than five decades mainly due to a territorial dispute over a chain
of Russian-held islands off northern Japan. 
</P>
