<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ukraine to Seek U.S. Funds for Chernobyl </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, November 15 (Xinhua) -- Ukrainian President Lenoid Kuchma
will start to visit the United States on November 18 in search of
funds for the troubled Chernobyl nuclear power plant, the
Ukrainian News Agency reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
During the three-day visit, Kuchma will hold talks with
U.S. Vice President Al Gore on the problems facing Chernobyl.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference on Friday, Ukrainian Security Secretary
Vladimir Gorbulin described the Chernobyl plant as the world's
only facility of its kind whose status remains vague and
unspecified.
</P>
<P>
The sarcophagus over the No.4 reactor, which exploded in 1986
in the worst nuclear accident in history, still contains about 150
to 210 tons of fissionable fuel.
</P>
<P>
Removal of the fuel poses a major problem, he said.
</P>
<P>
Besides, Ukraine will have to reprocess the fuel for safe
storage. To make the "Shelter" facility more technically reliable
and environmentally friendly, Ukraine will have to equip it with
sophisticated and costly monitoring devices to watch the physical
processes inside the sarcophagus.
</P>
<P>
Ukrainian experts estimate that the renovation project will
cost 750 U.S. dollars. The G-7 group has agreed to give Ukraine
300 million dollars in exchange for the complete shutdown of the
whole plant before 2000.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine itself has also promised to spend about 100 million
dollars to keep the sarcophagus in a proper condition.
</P>
<P>
All of the original four reactors at Chernobyl are shut down
now. No.4 and No.2 reactors ended up in accidents in 1986 and 1992
respectively. The other two have been shut down, one according to
a G-7 group agreement, the other for repair. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
