<HEADLINE> Swedish Firms Get Ready for Euro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, November 15 (Xinhua) -- Although Sweden will not be
among the first countries to introduce the single European
currency on January 1, 1999, some of Swedish largest firms are
preparing themselves for the transition, a local press report said
today.
</P>
<P>
"Customers in countries where the single currency has been
introduced will ask to be billed in euros, and we will accommodate
them," said Lars G. Malmer, spokesman for Sweden's bearing
manufacturer SKF.
</P>
<P>
"We see the euro as an opportunity to create a common financial
language in the group," said Kerstin Rendahl from a forestry firm,
Stora. Rendahl is in charge of the company's single currency
policy.
</P>
<P>
Several other firms also noted that investors will want
corporate reports in the European currency if the Stockholm
Exchange decides to record stock prices in euros in 1999.
</P>
<P>
"Therefore, we will present an abbreviated version of our
annual report for 1999 in the euro, while the full-length report
will still be in Swedish krona," said Ann Westergren Ekstedt, who
is responsible for coordinating the single currency project in
Ericsson, one of Sweden's major oil company. 
</P>
