<HEADLINE> Brazil's International Reserves Go Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, November 15 (Xinhua) -- Brazil's international
reserves dropped 9.3 billion U.S. dollars from 62.1 billion to
52.8 billion dollars by the end of October, the Central Bank said
today.
</P>
<P>
It was the lowest record of the country's international
reserves since January 1996.
</P>
<P>
By the end of September, the reserves totaled 61.1 billion
dollars, and by October 15 they rose to 62.1 billion dollars, but
quickly declined to 52.8 billion dollars by the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
The bank attributed the sharp drop within less than 15 days to
the country's financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
On October 28-30, the Central Bank had to hold 11 auctions of
dollars to contain the crisis and prevent a devaluation of the
national currency, the real.
</P>
<P>
Also in October, the government spent more than 1.2 billion
dollars in the repayment of foreign debt, the bank said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
