<DOCNO> XIE19971116.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South China Gets Closer To Goal Of Making Healthy City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, November 16 (Xinhua) -- The capital of China's island
province of Hainan in south China was chosen as the first city in
China by the World Health Organization for a healthy city pilot
project in 1995 and is close to reaching its goal.
</P>
<P>
Its goal is to stop the ecological crisis that resulted from
rapid industrialization and urbanization and to have a healthy
environment.
</P>
<P>
The city has over 500 kilometers of roads. There are 1,300
hectares of urban grassy areas and an afforestation rate of 39
percent. Noise, dust and water quality controls are up to state
standards, and the city disposes of 800 tons of waste every day,
and 95 percent of the residents have running water.
</P>
<P>
The city's nine-year compulsory education is working well, with
100 percent of school-age children in school. There are courses on
hygiene at all the city's primary and middle schools.
</P>
<P>
Haikou has pushed health care in urban and rural areas and has
had some success in increasing the life expectancy and reducing
the death rate.  
</P>
</TEXT>
