<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0030 GMT, November 16 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- Bosnian Prime Minister Haris Silajdzic wrapped
up his two-day official visit here Saturday, during which he held
talks with Kuwait leaders on strengthening ties between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said in an interview with local Kuwait news
agency Kuna before leaving "We wish to promote economic ties with
Kuwait as our political relations are already strong."
</P>
<P>
Kuwait and Bosnia have similarities as to geography, population
and military force, he said, expressing hope that superpowers
would restore security and stability in the region. (Kuwait-Bosnia)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
YANGON -- Myanmar carried out a major reshuffle of cabinet
ministers Saturday following the formation of the State Peace and
Development Council (SPDC), a new governing body replacing the
former State Law and Order Restoration Council (SLORC).
</P>
<P>
In the 39-member new cabinet, Senior-General Than Shwe still
holds posts of prime minister and defense minister, while the
posts of two deputy prime ministers remain unchanged, according to
an official announcement this evening. (Myanmar-Cabinet Reshuffle)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- The bodies of the four Americans who were killed
Wednesday by unidentified gunmen in Karachi, Pakistan's biggest
city, were flown back Saturday to the United States, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
The chartered Airbus flight No 993 of the Canadian Sky Services
which carried the bodies left Karachi, capital of Sindh province
for Maryland at about 3 p.m., the officials said.
(Pakistan-American Bodies)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin Saturday fired two
senior privatization officials Maxim Boiko and Pyotr Mostovoi for
their involvement in the scandal over high fees received for
writing an as-of-yet unpublished book.
</P>
<P>
Also embroiled in the scandal was the first Deputy Prime
Minister Anatoly Chubais and two other officials, who reportedly
received 90,000 dollars each for writing a book entitled "A
History of Russian Privatization."
</P>
<P>
The authors constitute the bulk of Russia's privatization team.
</P>
<P>
The book involved the authors in the scandal because of
allegations that the payment is a bribe in disguise.
(Russia-Politics-Book Scandal)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Iraqi Foreign Minister Mohammed Saeed al-Sahhaf
Saturday renewed the threat to shoot down any U.S. U-2 spy plane
overflying Iraq on U.N. arms inspection missions.
</P>
<P>
"Surely we'll shoot it down" if the surveillance plane resumes
overflight again, al-Sahhaf said while fielding questions from
reporters at a news briefing here this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
In his statement, the foreign minister lashed out at the
U.S. hostile policy against Iraq and its objective to keep the
sanctions in place and use them as a tool to topple President
Saddam Hussein. (Iraq-US-FM)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. President Bill Clinton and British Prime
Minister Tony Blair have agreed to diplomatic solutions in
pressuring Iraqi President Saddam Hussein to reverse course in the
latest arms inspection crisis, a senior U.S. official said on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, conferring for about 10 minutes with Blair from Air
Force One while in flight from Las Vegas to Sacramento on
Saturday, discussed how to maintain unity on the N.N. Security
Council in "seeking a diplomatic solution" to the arms inspection
crisis, the senior official said. (US-Iraq-Arms Inspections)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkish government Saturday called on Baghdad to
abide by the U.N. resolutions in order to avoid a military
confrontation with the United States.
</P>
<P>
The appeal was issued after Turkish Deputy Prime Minister
Bulent Ecevit, Defense Minister Ismet Sezgin and other government
and military officials discussed the Iraqi tensions, the Anatolia
News Agency said.
</P>
<P>
"We hope the current tensions will be defused without use of
force," said a senior government source, who preferred not be
named. (Turkey-Iraq)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NICOSIA -- Turkish Chief of General Staff Ismail Hakki Karadayi
said Saturday in northern Cyprus that Turkey will do whatever it
can to defend the interests of the Turkish Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a banquet in Girne, a port city, marking the 14th
anniversary of the founding of "the Turkish Republic of Northern
Cyprus," Karadayi said that Turkey will maintain its military
existence on the eastern Mediterranean island. (Turkey-Cyprus)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WARSAW -- Polish President Aleksander Kwasniewski left here
Saturday to begin a state visit to China, which he hopes will help
strengthen economic relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
During the five-day visit, the first by a Polish head of state
since 1959, Kwasniewski is scheduled to meet Chinese leaders to
discuss bilateral relations and international issues of common
concern. (Poland-China-Visit) 
</P>
