<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Belgian Eleven Qualify for World Cup Finals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, November 15 (Xinhua) -- Goals from Luis Oliveira and
Luc Nilis today lifted Belgium to join Yugoslavia, Croatia and
Italy as the last European teams to qualify for next year's World
Cup finals.
</P>
<P>
The Belgians won on an aggregate of 3-2.
</P>
<P>
With a 1-1 away game at hand, the Belgian Red Demons sealed
the return leg of the two-game playoff in a match that saw
jitters in the opening 15 minutes and chilly rains in more than
40 minutes.
</P>
<P>
Oliveira, who did not play in Dublin on October 11, beat an
offside trap at the 24th minute and the Belgian striker sped off
an Irish defender before beating the opposing goalkeeper to the
goal for the morale-boosting opener.
</P>
<P>
The striker then created a freekick just outside the Irish
penalty area after he was brought down during another solo run
for the goal.
</P>
<P>
Nilis, who was on target in Dublin for the Belgians, lobbed
the freekick just over the crossbar.
</P>
<P>
But a 68th-minute tie-breaking winner made Nilis the toast of
a capacity crowd at the Heysel Stadium. The playmaker resorted
to a smart fake maneuver to run away from two defenders inside
the penalty box and chipped in a neat pass from left.
</P>
<P>
Substitute Ray Houghton once tied the game for the visitors
and rekindled the hope of Irish quanlifying for the cup finale.
He headed in an endline cross for a 58th-minute equalizer.
</P>
<P>
The Irish squandered several of their scoring chances.
</P>
<P>
Gary Kelly's grazing shot from close range went just on the
wrong side of the right Belgian goal post six minutes upon
resumption.
</P>
<P>
At one time both sides played a little tough and the referee
had to fish out a couple of yellow cards before sending off
Ireland's David Conolly at the 81st minute for foul tackle a
second time in the game.
</P>
<P>
Elsewhere in the other European playoff games, Predrag
Mijatovic celebrated a scoring spree with four goals in a 5-0
trouncing over Hungary in Belgrade. The Real Madrid striker
scored a hat-trick in the away game for a 7-1 win in Budapest.
Yugoslavia scored 12 goals in all and conceded one goal in the
two games.
</P>
<P>
A 27th-minute goal by Alen Boksic sent Croatia to its first
ever World Cup final. Croatia held hosts Ukraine for a
one-goal-each draw and a 3-1 winning aggregate.
</P>
<P>
Pierluigi Casiraghi scored Italy's lone goal in a hard-fought
game against visiting Russia. But the lone goal was enough to
secure Italy a berth in France. The Italians pinned hosts Russia
down to a 1-1 tie in the first leg on October 11 in a snowstorm.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971116.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia Qualify for World Cup Finals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, November 15 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslavia claimed a berth in
World Cup finals after beating Hungary 5-0 in the second leg of
playoff here on Saturday, thanks for four goals from Predrag
Mijatovic.
</P>
<P>
Mijatovic, who had a hat-trick in the first-leg 7-1 win in
Budapest, opened scoring with a 44th-minute volley from Dragan
Stojkovic's cross after Savo Milosevic took their lead in the 17th
minute on Stojkovic's free kick.
</P>
<P>
Mijatovic again converted a penalty one minute later and
completed his hat-trick in the 71st minute, finishing outstanding
efforts from Stojkovic and Dejan Savicevic.
</P>
<P>
The Real Madrid striker sealed the victory a minute from time
to lift Yugoslavia qualifying on an aggregate of 12-1. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971116.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kwasniewski Left Warsaw to Start China Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, November 8 (Xinhua) -- Polish President Aleksander
Kwasniewski left here today to begin a state visit to China, which
he hopes will help strengthen economic relations between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
During the five-day visit, the first by a Polish head of state
since 1959, Kwasniewski is scheduled to meet Chinese leaders to
discuss bilateral relations and international issues of common
concern.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Chinese reporters on the eve of his visit,
Kwasniewski said his visit would be a new beginning in the history
of Sino-Polish relations and would give a great hope for the
development of bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
He said he would "take full advantage of the visit" and
"enhance dialogue and cooperation with China."
</P>
<P>
The potential of the Sino-Polish relationship, especially that
of economic cooperation has not been fully tapped, he said, adding
that time is ripe now to fully tap such potential.
</P>
<P>
Noting that Poland and China used to share a good tradition of
economic cooperation, the president said that in recent years,
such cooperation was weakened for various reasons. Now, he said,
the two countries should explore new ways of cooperation by
strengthening exchanges and mutual understanding.
</P>
<P>
He also said the two countries should strengthen dialogue, not
only at the central government level, but also at the level of
local governments.
</P>
<P>
Kwasniewski said Poland highly valued the role China plays on
the international stage. As Poland also plays its appropriate role
in world affairs, it will benefit both Poland and China to have
good cooperation in international politics, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that he visited China in 1988 as the minister of youths
and sports of the former government. He made a private visit to
China in 1989. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971116.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany Trounce South Africans 3-0 in Soccer Friendly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, November 15 (Xinhua) -- Hosts Germany trounced South
Africa 3-0 in a soccer friendly at Duesseldorf on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The German team surged to a 2-0 lead within 32 minutes thanks
to the goals from Dieter Hamann and Oliver Bierhoff.
</P>
<P>
Hamann, a striker from BAyern Munich who made his international
debut in the match, got onto a rebound and looped in a 20-meter
drive in the 13th minute to give Germany a 1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
At the 32nd minute, Thomas Haessler sent cross to Bierhoff who
beat South African goal-keeper Mark Anderson with a header.
</P>
<P>
The host team kept up pressure in the second half and Joerg
Heinrich headed home a cross from Mario Basler at the 69th minute
to seal up the perfect victory for the German team. 
</P>
</TEXT>
