<HEADLINE> U.S. Banking Industry in Good Shape </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, November 15 (Xinhua) -- The robust economy has
ensured strong loan demand thus giving an impetus to the banking
industry in the United States.
</P>
<P>
Income of the nation's 71 "superregional" banks from lending
rose 15 percent to 144 billion U.S. dollars in 1996 while their
noninterest income from bank accounts, asset management and
trading profits grew 28 percent, local newspaper Investor's
Business Daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
Low inflation and stable interests are among the factors
contributing to the sustained growth of the banking industry.
</P>
<P>
The American Bankers Association considers banks with assets of
more than 10 billion dollars as superregionals who own a combined
assets of 2.25 trillion dollars.
</P>
<P>
They are not in the rank of the country's "big ten" banks whose
assets totaling 2 trillion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The superregionals' assents have been expanding since 1991 with
1996 recording a 20 percent increase. The growth prospect for this
year was set for 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
The superregionals' main markets include home, consumer and
middle-market business loans, credit cards, and checking and
savings.
</P>
<P>
The banking industry is also featured by merger and
acquisition, the latest case being the 15.5 billion dollar
acquisition of Florida's Barnett Banks by North Carolina's
NationsBank Corp..
</P>
<P>
Banks not only merge businesses of the same line, but also
other financial firms like brokers. Today's superregionals cover
also consumer loans, investing, trust, brokerage and underwriting.
</P>
<P>
As the nation's economy shows no sign of slowing, and baby
boomers are saving for education of their next generations and
their own retirement, banks are poised for growth if they know
enough how to manage risks, analysts said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
